<TEXT>
a judge who admitted being married to two 
women at the same time was suspended wednesday by the oregon 
supreme court 
multnomah county district judge robert kirkman will be suspended 
with pay effective monday pending a final decision by the court 
the supreme court action came after the oregon judicial fitness 
commission unanimously recommended he be removed from office for 
premeditated and calculating criminal misconduct 
during the commissions disciplinary hearing in september 
kirkman 47 admitted he was married to two women at the same time 
he also admitted he had shown his second wife a forged divorce 
decree before he married her 
kirkman showed jane kingsbury his second wife the forged 
divorce decree in 1984 they were married in april 1987 by 
kirkmans boss judge donald londer 
later that year the marriage was annulled after kingsbury 
learned that kirkman was still married to his first wife sue 
it was not very smart going through the ceremony and it was 
not very smart to ask judge londer to perform the ceremony 
kirkman admitted in september 
kirkman and kingsbury remarried the following january shortly 
after his divorce from his first wife was final 
based on kirkmans admissions the commission found that he 
forged a court document that he falsely represented on a marriage 
license that he was divorced and that he remarried while still 
married to his first wife 
to his credit judge kirkman admitted that he knew his 
behavior was wrong and illegal when he committed it the 
commission found 
the supreme court said a hearing to make a final ruling probably 
will be held in januay possible sanctions range from reprimand to 
removal from office the commissions findings are only advisory to 
the supreme court 
judge kirkman has conducted his personal life in a way that 
has brought discredit and dishonor both to himself and to the 
judicial system the judicial fitness commission said 
kirkmans attorney said he would ask the supreme court for a 
lesser penalty 
naturally we are quite disappointed said garr m king who 
represented kirkman at the commission hearing 
</TEXT>
