<TEXT>
sen jesse helms will try to slip a new 
antiobscenity noose around the national endowment for the arts 
when the senate begins debate today on the emotional issue of 
federal support for artistic works that some view as offensive 
helms a conservative north carolina republican is leading the 
fight to impose explicit new curbs on the neas grantmaking 
powers he is opposed by a bipartisan group of senators who favor 
having the courts decide whether neasupported works are obscene 
on monday night helms introduced a proposal to forbid the arts 
endowment to spend federal funds on any works that depict or 
describe in a patently offensive way sexual or excretory 
activities or organs 
the ban proposed by helms omits any mention of obscenity by 
name apparently to satisfy objections by opponents of such curbs 
that the nea has no business making judgments about obscenity 
at midday today the senate planned to start seven hours of 
debate on the helms amendment and a rival plan backed by sens 
orrin hatch rutah and claiborne pell dri that would 
penalize grant recipients who are later convicted of violating 
obscenity laws 
the proposed helms ban if approved would replace a laundry 
list of antiobscenity curbs that congress slapped on the nea a 
year ago the bill up for senate action today would renew those 
restrictions extend the endowments life through next september 
and trim its proposed 175 million budget by 5 million 
the current ban forbids nea support for works that may be 
considered obscene including but not limited to depictions of 
sadomasochism homoeroticism the sexual exploitation of children 
or individuals engaged in sex acts and which when taken as a 
whole do not have serious literary artistic political or 
scientific value 
that helmsinspired ban was approved amid an escalating 
political controversy over nea grants for exhibitions of works by 
photographer robert mapplethorpe and artist andres serrano which 
helms and other conservative lawmakers denounced as obscene and 
sacrilegious 
