<TEXT>
a prominent central asian writer has become the 
first person to quit president mikhail s gorbachevs advisory 
council a move symbolic of frustrations with the stagnation of 
soviet reform efforts 
chingiz aitmatov a writer from kirghiz once touted as a 
candidate for the nobel prize in literature confirmed in an 
interview tuesday that he is leaving the presidential council to 
become ambassador to luxembourg 
rumors of aitmatovs appointment to the diplomatic post had 
caused a sensation in the soviet press 
the prestigious council which gorbachev created this year as an 
alternative to the politburo is one of the most important of the 
newly established or reformed soviet political institutions 
young people want to be involved in politics but i really 
dont care about it said aitmatov 62 looking worn and tired 
during an interview in his office 
he said that his appointment to luxembourg has the blessing of 
the president gorbachev and awaits only the agreement of the 
luxembourg government 
although he said he was not a pessimist he was generally 
downbeat about the future of the soviet union in keeping with the 
gloom that has gripped the country with the onset of winter and the 
apparent failure of what had promised to be a bountiful harvest 
aitmatov dismissed people who say the total collapse of the 
soviet empire would be good 
it is a sick organism but a living one he said 
fragmentation and disorder inside this organism would not benefit 
anyone inside or outside the country 
aitmatov said his duties on the presidential council included 
ethnic problems but otherwise he declined to shed much light on 
the inner workings of the council one of the most important of the 
newly created or reformed soviet political institutions 
gorbachev created the council earlier this year as an 
alternative to the politburo the party body that formerly made 
important national decisions 
the list of members reads like a westernstyle cabinet 
including the ministers of defense foreign affairs and interior 
the state planning chief and the head of the kgb security police 
