<TEXT>
a gathering of balkan foreign ministers 
that opened today is one more sign that albania europes most 
backward country is gradually cracking out of its stalinist shell 
the twoday meeting is only the second such gathering since 
world war ii and the first highlevel international meeting in 
tirana in decades 
albanias government virtually sealed the tiny country for 
years but has been seeking slowly to end its isolation 
the gathering opened with calls for closer cooperation in the 
region which in the past has been a powder keg of europe 
but differences immediately emerged with greece taking a swipe 
at albania on the treatment of its greek minority 
in his opening speech albanian president ramiz alia called for 
a zone of peace and security in the balkans greece turkey 
yugoslavia albania bulgaria and romania 
the meeting underscored dramatic changes in europe since the 
first balkans meeting in belgrade in february 1988 
the fall of communism in eastern europe has brought new 
freedoms but has also made for an upsurge in nationalist feelings 
especially in the balkans where the mix of of religions and 
ethnic groups has always been volatile 
yugoslavia where ethnic divisions are so fierce that the 
country may split apart is at odds with albania over the yugoslav 
province of kosovo an ancient heartland of the serbian republic 
bordering albania 
greece and turkey are traditional enemies divided today over 
the fate of cyprus 
albania and greece disagree over albanias alleged mistreatment 
of its estimated 400000 greek minority 
bulgaria and romania are quarrelling over crossborder 
pollution 
the serbs in yugosalvia want more rights for the ethnic serbs in 
romania 
and bulgaria greece and yugoslavia disagree over who really 
should control the territory known today as the southern yugoslav 
republic of macedonia 
bulgarias foreign minister luben gotsev supported by his 
greek counterpart antonis samaras proposed forming a secretariat 
in the bulgarian capital sofia to coordinate regional 
cooperation 
gotsev samaras and romanias foreign minister adrian nastase 
all urged measures to overcome the regions ethnic religious and 
historical differences 
bulgaria and romania proposed that a balkan summit be held next 
year romania urged that a code of conduct on ethnic matters be 
considered 
samaras apparently referring to albanias treatment of its 
greek minority asked the session can we call a country free if 
any man or woman in this country is not allowed to exercise fully 
their religious rights does this not also apply to political 
and economic rights 
in the wake of eastern europes revolutions albania has 
embarked on cautious domestic reform and moved to end its isolation 
abroad 
it restored diplomatic ties with the soviet union and is seeking 
the same links with the united states 
the balkan nation of 3 million people has also declared it wants 
to join the 34nation helsinki process albania was the only 
european nation not to sign the helsinki final act in 1975 
to be admitted albania is likely to have to take human rights 
reform further than it has to date 
on tuesday as diplomats and journalists arrived in tirana for 
the balkan meeting albanias communistrun daily published the 
draft of an election law that for the first time permits secret 
ballots and multiple candidacies for each of the 250 seats in the 
communistrun parliament 
however the draft stopped short of permitting any new political 
parties and a legal expert indicated alia does not intend to 
abandon oneparty rule 
there will be pluralism of opinions aleks luarasi told 
reporters but there wont be any party pluralism 
