<DOCNO> AP901024-0064 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a potentially deadly bacterial cousin of toxic 
shock syndrome is on the rise targeting both children and adults 
scientists say 
researchers at a national microbiology conference said tuesday 
the illness is a severe streptococcal infection strep is 
frequently thought of as the cause of strep throat but in rare 
cases it can cause extremely serious infections such as the 
pneumonia that killed muppets creator jim henson in may 
three years ago researchers began to talk of toxic shock caused 
by strep not the staph bacteria linked to tampon use toxic shock 
is characterized by low blood pressure rash peeling skin and 
multiorgan infections 
researchers at the centers for disease control and in pima 
county ariz studied 128 cases of groupa strep infections in 10 
hospitals in the tucson area from 1985 to 1990 none of the 54 
cases from 1985 to 1987 resembled toxic shock syndrome but six of 
the 74 infections studied from 1988 to 1990 did 
the pattern is clear dr charles hoge of the cdc reported at 
the interscience conference on antimicrobial agents and 
chemotherapy streptococcal toxic shock syndrome was 
significantly more likely to occur after 1988 
one of the six patients died for all the groupa strep 
infection patients in the study the death rate was 20 percent 
toxic shock syndrome gets its name from the toxins produced by 
the bacteria at fault lab findings from the arizona study suggest 
a toxin may also be the culprit in the serious strep infections 
hoge said 
three of the arizona toxic shocklike cases occurred in 
children and other researchers also reported waves of serious 
strep infections in youngsters 
doctors at childrens mercy hospital in kansas city mo 
reported that eight of their 29 cases of groupa strep from 1971 to 
1990 had symptoms resembling toxic shock syndrome the hospital has 
seen four cases this year 
we have not had four children previously in one year with 
multisystemic streptococcal syndrome said dr mary anne 
jackson were trying to draw the attention of clinicians to this 
entity tell them to think of this 
doctors make a diagnosis based on blood tests showing group 
a streptococcal bacteria accompanied by a syndrome of symptoms 
including low blood pressure and shock skin rash flaking or 
inflamed skin and the spread of infection to organs such as the 
kidneys or heart 
doctors at dalhousie university in halifax nova scotia 
reported 16 such cases over 10 years 
strep was once the frequent cause of serious illnesses such as 
scarlet fever and rheumatic fever but the most dangerous strains 
for the most part faded from view around the 1940s 
henson was the most famous recent victim of severe streptococcal 
illness he died of a rapidly spreading pneumonia when groupa 
strep infections proceed to the bloodstream the fatality rate is 
20 percent to 30 percent 
