<TEXT>
leftist unions staged a nationwide 
strike today paralyzing public transportation and many businesses 
the military denounced the action as a communist bid to foment 
insurrection 
suspected communist rebels burned at least 17 vehicles to force 
drivers to join the strike and police said at least two people 
were slain and four injured in strikerelated violence police said 
earlier today that two other people had died in a bus attack but 
later said that report was mistaken 
at least 43 people were arrested including medardo roda leader 
of a militant transport union police said roda may be charged with 
sedition and other offenses linked to the violence 
crispin beltran chairman of the militant may first movement 
that called the strike went into hiding following reports he would 
also be arrested 
the strike crippled public transportation in manila and several 
provincial cities department stores banks hotels factories and 
other major enterprises closed or operated with skeletal crews 
it was unclear whether most absentees supported the strike or 
simply were unable to get rides to work 
the may first movement was demanding a 150 raise in the 
minimum daily wage a 42 percent increase 
officially the minimum daily wage in manila is 350 but a 
recent government survey shows 55 percent of businesses in the 
capital pay less minimum wageearners already are too poor to buy 
meat and inflation is running at 12 percent 
president corazon aquino had urged workers not to join the 
strike saying the nations fragile economy could not afford the 
wage increase 
we are not giving in to the 38peso demand a government 
spokesman adolf azcuna said 
speaking in a radio interview from his hiding place beltran 
said the work stoppage would continue thursday if the workers 
demands were not met 
the nationwide strike the most extensive since 1987 also 
marked the first time the communists had taken such an active 
visible role in a labor protest 
the chief of staff gen renato de villa denounced the strike 
as communistdominated and said the violence was the work of 
guerrillas of the communist new peoples army 
the rebels have decided to use this strike to promote their 
insurrectionary situation de villa told reporters 
leftist leader nathaniel santiago blamed the government for 
todays unrest 
this anger of our society is a natural reaction to the 
governments turning its back on the people and a realization that 
it is futile to deal with a government that is numb to the 
suffering of its people santiago said 
the strike appeared most successful in the capital and 
surrounding areas of central luzon island a longtime communist 
stronghold 
officials said about 20 percent of the labor department 
employees did not show up for work and most government agencies 
allowed employees to leave early 
among the firms shut down was atlas consolidated mining co in 
cebu the largest copper producer in asia where 10000 workers 
walked out schools and colleges in manila and surrounding 
provinces were also closed 
authorities at the us clark air base in angeles city north of 
manila imposed travel restrictions on base personnel for security 
reasons 
