<TEXT>
pakistanis turned out in unexpectedly 
small numbers today for a bitterly contested national election 
widely considered a referendum on the dismissal of benazir bhutto 
as prime minister 
at least four people were killed and 11 injured in disputes 
involving rival parties officials said and there were scattered 
reports of voter harassment intimidation and ballotbox theft 
the monthlong campaign claimed at least a dozen lives 
tens of thousands of heavily armed soldiers paramilitary troops 
and police patrolled throughout the country during the voting 
todays general elections were only the fifth in pakistan since its 
1947 inception and never before was the military deployed in such 
large numbers during polling 
about 50 million people were eligible to vote but election 
officias said turnout was light perhaps reflecting cynicism about 
the future of democracy in pakistan 
ms bhutto claims her aug 6 dismissal amounted to a 
constitutional coup by president ghulam ishaq khan and that 
abuse of power charges filed against her are baseless slander 
after casting her own vote in her ancestral hometown at larkana 
in southern pakistan the former prime minister predicted victory 
for her party 
we have turned the tables on them said ms bhutto who was 
unopposed in her bid for reelection to parliament if we win 
they will have no choice but to let us form the next government 
analysts predicted the vote would be close between ms bhuttos 
leftleaning pakistan peoples party and three smaller allied 
parties and the islamic democratic alliance a looseknit coalition 
of 18 parties united only by their dislike for ms bhutto and 
strained by individual ambitions 
voters in ms bhuttos hometown of karachi lined up outside 
polling booths three hours before they opened the longest lines 
were in the sprawling slum district of lyari where ms bhuttos 
jailed husband asif ali zardari 38 is a candidate 
lines also formed in parts of the eastern city f lahore the 
longtime stronghold of ms bhuttos opponents 
but at polling stations elsewhere officials reported turnouts 
ranging from 10 to 40 percent during the nine hours of voting no 
overall figures on the turnout were immediately available 
the government which is controlled by ms bhuttos foes filed 
a seventh abuse of power charge against her just hours before the 
polls opened today 
but the campaign to destroy the 37yearold ms bhutto 
politically may have backfired it halted the steady decline in her 
popularity and helped galvanize the disgruntled rankandfile 
within her party 
just hours before the polls opened a candidate of ms bhuttos 
rightwing opposition was gunned down along with five companions 
news reports said earlier this week several of ms bhuttos party 
workers were killed 
police refused to link the latest killing to the elections but 
the prime minister in the army backed caretaker government ghulam 
mustafa jatoi suggested that ms bhuttos party loyalists were 
involved 
the victim was contesting a rural seat in punjab province where 
60 percent of the countrys 102 million people live and where the 
outcome is expected to be decided he and his companions were 
killed by gunmen who fired on their vehicle during an 11thhour 
tour of his constituency 
in addition to charging ms bhutto and seven former cabinet 
ministers with abuse of power the caretaker government had her 
husband arrested on oct 10 for the alleged kidnapping and 
extortion of a pakistaniborn british citizen 
more than 1300 candidates are vying for 214 of the 217 seats in 
the national assembly the policymaking lower house of parliament 
that will choose pakistans next prime minister 
two independent candidates were elected unopposed while voting 
was postponed in one constituency because one of the candidates was 
shot and killed 
ms bhuttos leftleaning pakistan peoples party and three 
smaller parties faced the islamic democratic alliance a looseknit 
coalition of 18 diverse parties united only by their dislike for 
ms bhutto 
in a nation with a literacy rate of less than 25 percent voters 
placed their thumbprint next to their partys symbol ms bhuttos 
symbol is the arrow the islamic democratic alliance uses the 
bicycle 
most analysts doubted either side would emerge with an outright 
victory resulting in another shaky coalition government as fragile 
as the last 
whoever forms the next government will be forced by the 
constitution to share power with the president and the countrys 
most powerful institution the military 
at least 55 international pollwatchers monitored todays 
balloting and their assessment could affect hundreds of millions 
of dollars in vital economic and military aid from the west 
in december 1988 ms bhutto became the first woman to lead a 
modern moslem nation her accession to power followed the first 
free elections in pakistan after more than a decade of military 
rule 
but ms bhuttos stewardship was troubled and ishaq khan called 
her government pakistans most corrupt and incompetent ever when he 
dismissed her 
if found guilty on the abuse of power charges ms bhutto could 
be denied her seat in parliament and banned from politics for seven 
years 
she has insisted her government was competent and clean and 
called the president a liar cheater and dictator she said she 
would demand his resignation if she returns to power 
ishaq khan 73 was a stalwart of gen mohammad zia ulhaq who 
overthrew ms bhuttos father the late prime minister zulfikar ali 
bhutto in a 1977 coup zia ruled pakistan until his death in a 
stillunexplained plane crash in august 1988 
