minority tutsi tribe invaded from its northern neighbor uganda 
belgiums foreign minister mark eyskens said he was told the 
ceasefire began this morning but there were reports that the 
rebels had violated it 
eyskens told a news conference in nairobi that he learned of the 
truce in a telephone call from his rwandan counterpart casimir 
bizimungu 
rwanda in agreeing to the ceasefire accepted the rebel demand 
that both sides maintain their positions while officials pursue a 
negotiated end to the conflict eyskens said 
the rebel rwandese patriotic front has said its fighters cannot 
withdraw from the country because uganda has refused to allow their 
return 
belgium rwandas former colonial ruler has been leading 
international efforts to settle the conflict peacefully 
eyskens was joined at the news conference by belgian prime 
minister wilfried martens and defense minister guy coeme 
soon after the rebel invasion belgium sent several hundred 
troops to rwanda to protect its nationals and embassy but it has 
insisted the monitoring force be made up of africans 
we think it is the responsibility of the africans and the 
organization of african unity should play a major role said 
eyskens adding belgium would provide logistical and financial 
support to the force 
he would not disclose the size of the proposed force or say how 
much money the belgium force would cost 
france also sent troops to protect its citizens and embassy in 
the tiny central african country while zaire sent up to 1000 
soldiers who have been fighting alongside the rwandan army 
the rebels have insisted the foreign troops must leave rwanda 
before they would open peace talks they also have demanded rwandan 
troops stop killing civilians and the government release thousands 
of people arrested for allegedly supporting the insurgency 
it was not immediately known if the rebels were standing by 
those conditions 
ugandas president yoweri museveni on monday announced the 
rebels had told him they were ready to accept a truce 
