<TEXT>
china has pulled its economy out of a serious 
slump by pumping more funds into moneylosing state factories and 
building up inventories according to official statistics released 
wednesday 
industrial output grew 5 percent in the third quarter of the 
year from 1989s third quarter including a 75 percent jump in 
september a spokesman for the state statistical bureau zhang 
zhongji told a news conference 
chinese industry went into a slump last year after two years of 
reduced state credit and purchases millions of small factories 
shut down and even some large state factories furloughed portions 
of their work forces 
worried about possible social unrest the govenrment this year 
loosened limits on bank loans and resumed some construction 
projects 
zhang said the government spent 84 billion in subsidies to 
moneylosing factories and 42 billion in price subsidies to 
control inflation during the first nine months of the year 
inflation remains at about 2 percent and liberal economists 
have argued that the economy is healthy enough to resume the 
process of replacing central planning with market forces 
however top leaders in the ruling communist party remain in 
debate over the issue they have been unable to reach agreement on 
a key document setting forth the next five years economic program 
the government subsidies helped restart production but much of 
the new output simply went into warehouses zhang said state 
factories piled up inventories worth 253 billion by the end of 
september 50 percent larger than their inventories one year 
earlier 
overall profits at state factories fell 579 percent and 
profits at stateowned stores fell 737 percent zhang said 
onethird of all state factories actually lost money for total 
losses of 42 billion during the first nine months of the year 
zhang blamed sluggish consumer demand for the state sectors 
poor showing however earlier official reports have noted the tiny 
private sector and collectively owned factories in rural areas have 
consistently outperformed the state sector regardless of market 
conditions 
about 56 percent of the work force is officially classed as 
unemployed but western economists say the figure could be much 
higher 
despite these problems zhang said the economy is developing 
toward a more favorable direction he predicted increases in 
production and construction from october through december 
</TEXT>
