<TEXT>
a study has found no extra leukemia deaths among 
young people living near nuclear plants in france in contrast to 
reports from britain 
scientists studied cancer deaths between 1968 and 1987 among 
people younger than age 25 who lived near six nuclear power or 
reprocessing plants 
the researchers focused on populations living at distances of 
less than 31 miles 31 to 62 miles 62 miles to 81 miles and 
81 miles to 99 miles 
researchers found more deaths from hodgkins disease than 
expected but said the difference was not statistically 
significant 
the work is reported in thursdays issue of the british journal 
nature by researchers at the gustave roussy institute in villejuif 
france 
previous reports found more leukemia deaths than expected in 
people younger than 25 who lived near the sellafield nuclear 
reprocessing plant in england and the dounreay nuclear complex in 
scotland 
those results may be due to higher discharges of radioactive 
material than in france or other factors such as infections the 
french researchers speculated 
in september national cancer institute researchers said they 
found no extra cancer risk in or near counties with nuclear 
installations in the united states the study did not assess risk 
in more limited areas around the plants 
</TEXT>
