<TEXT>
the 70yearold soviet national trade union 
organization voted today to dissolve itself and to form a voluntary 
association of unions the state news agency tass reported 
the meeting in moscow coincided with a congress of miners 
occurring in the ukrainian city of donestsk to form the nations 
first independent trade union 
during their weeklong conference the miners plan to consider a 
national strike to enforce their economic and political demands 
the congress is an outgrowth of the nationwide coal strike that 
gripped the country in july 1989 
with president mikhail s gorbachev in attendance 2500 
delegates to the central council of trade unions meeting in moscow 
voted the council out of existence and formed an alliance of 
industrial and regional unions tass said 
the council was an umbrella organization of trade unions 
representing an estimated 140 million soviet workers 
it was not clear whether the miners union would be allowed or 
would want to join the newly reformed national trade union 
organization 
delegates to the national congress in moscow being held two 
years ahead of scheduled moved quickly to break with the communist 
economic system 
deputy chief vladimir scherbakov said the council increasingly 
lagged behind profound changes acute and complex processes of real 
life which inevitably prompted a crisis of trust in its 
structures he said the revamped organization would no longer 
demand a monopoly on workers loyalty 
tass said the decision to hold the official conference two years 
early was extraordinary no official reason was given but it 
appeared designed to coincide with the miners meeting in donetsk 
the open bidding for workers hearts in a country that once 
hailed itself as a workers paradise demonstrated the political 
importance that organizers place on bluecollar labor as the 
political and economic system opens up 
the miners strikes which started in the summer of 1989 began 
to protest working and living conditions and shortages of such 
basics as soap and medical care the miners quickly escalated their 
demands to include regional economic autonomy for the main mine 
regions such as the kuznetsk basin in siberia and the don river 
basin in the ukraine 
prime minister nikolai i ryzhkov persuaded the miners to return 
to work promising to meet most of their demands but most of the 
promises remain unfulfilled an issue that has spurred new strikes 
the strike committees meeting at their first conference in 
donetsk last summer demanded the promises be honored they also 
called for ryzhkovs government to resign and urged workers in 
other industries to cut their ties with the government and official 
unions 
the delegates at that congress proposed forming an independent 
trade union but postponed its actual formation until now to allow 
the new government of russian president boris n yeltsin to deal 
with the economic crisis 
