<TEXT>
transportation secretary samuel k skinner on 
wednesday announced new standards to protect car occupants during 
sideimpact collisions saying the regulation would prevent 500 
deaths a year 
the action ends more than a decade of haggling over how 
manufacturers should reinforce cars to help riders withstand side 
collisions more people die that way than in any other kind of 
automobile wreck except frontal collisions 
its been a long time coming skinner said at a news 
conference outside the capitol he stood near a demonstration car 
with its drivers side crushed inward and a crash dummy seated 
behind the wheel in a graphic illustration of the danger of side 
collisions 
manufacturers must meet the new standards in 10 percent of their 
new cars by 1994es to 25 percent in the 1995 mod the minimum risel 
year and 40 percent in 1996 by the 1997 model year all new cars 
must comply 
the changes will boost the average cars cost by about 50 a 
small price to pay for the prevention of the immense loss of life 
and suffering as a result of these side impacts skinner said 
the regulation is designed to reduce deaths and serious injuries 
caused by chest and pelvic injuries about 8000 people die and 
24000 are hurt seriously each year in side crashes 
rance institute for highway safety said the regulation 
was a longoverdue first step but was inadequate because it 
excludes protections from head injuries 
a substantial proportion of the most serious injuries that 
occur in side impacts are head injuries said brian oneill the 
groups president 
