<TEXT>
the editors of a weekly newspaper for haitians 
in miami were among the five winners announced wednesday of the 
annual maria moors cabot prizes for journalism that advances 
interamerican understanding 
the editors marc marcus garcia and elsie etheart are the 
first haitians to be awarded gold medals in the 52year history of 
the prizes they founded the french and creolelanguage haiti en 
marche in 1986 and also produce creole radio news programs in 
southern florida 
other winners to be honored in ceremonies at columbia 
university on thursday night were richard boudreaux los angeles 
times bureau chief in managua nicaragua alma guillermoprieto 
latin america correspondent for the new yorker magazine and other 
publications and huascar cajias kauffmann founder and columnist 
of presencia a daily newspaper in la paz bolivia 
the cabot prizes a gold medal and 1000 to each winner were 
established by godfrey lowell cabot of boston as a memorial to his 
wife they are awarded by the trustees of columbia on the 
recommendation of the universitys school of journalism 
garcia and etheart radio journalists in haiti in the 1970s 
were arrested and jailed in 1980 for reporting on the activities of 
the secret police they were expelled as subversives by dictator 
jeanclaude duvalier 
their newspaper in miami is read in canada and haiti and their 
news broadcasts reach nearly all the 120000 haitians in south 
florida 
boudreaux 42 has been a reporter 20 years he worked for the 
associated press for 16 years in new york argentina mexico chile 
and bolivia before joining the los angeles times 
guillermoprieto 41 a dancer before embarking on journalism 
performed with the ballet nacional de mexico in her native land and 
with harry sheppard elaine shipman and twyla tharp she began 
reporting in 1978 as a central american stringer for latin 
american newsletters the guardian of london and the washington 
post she was newsweeks south american bureau chief from 1986 to 
1987 and has written a book samba about brazil in addition to 
contributing long pieces to the new yorker 
cajias a champion of press freedom in bolivia founded 
presencia in 1952 and edited it until four years ago he also is a 
lawyer and has been a professor of both criminology and journalism 
in la paz he was his countrys ambassador to the vatican from 1986 
until last year and served as a delegate at international 
gatherings in vienna to discuss ways to combat drug trafficking 
</TEXT>
