<TEXT>
the national trade union organization 
voted to dissolve itself wednesday as coal miners gathered in the 
ukraine at the same time and announced plans to create the first 
mass independent union in soviet history 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev attended the meeting in 
moscow of the governmentsponsored national congress of trade 
unions whose 2500 delegates voted to reconstitute the 70yearold 
organization as a voluntary association of unions 
gorbachev told the meeting that he favored strong and 
independent unions the state news agency tass reported 
a meeting of the umbrella group representing about 140 million 
workers was called for this week two years ahead of schedule the 
dissolution of the organization appeared to be an effort to defuse 
the emergence of the radical miners union 
the miners holding their congress in the donetsk coal basin 
600 miles south of moscow have been threatening a repeat of the 
nationwide strikes that threatened to cripple the nation in july 
1989 
miner delegates from western siberia kazakhstan and the far 
north said they would not call a strike pending consideration of 
their complaints by the legislature of the russian republic now in 
session in moscow but they said they would create an independent 
union 
we will adopt a draft and we will go from here as the first 
members of an independent trade union said alexander adanidi a 
member of kuznetsk basin workers committee which started the 1989 
strike 
adanidi and other siberian miners complained that coal minister 
mikhail shchadov whose agency owns all mines and associated 
industries across the country had tried to undermine the 
legitimacy of the congress by contributing nearly 70000 to it 
shchadov was scheduled to address the congress thursday he was 
shouted down and driven from the hall when he spoke to a similar 
miners congress last summer 
at the congress of the governmentsponsored trade union 
association in moscow gorbachev urged delegates to keep in touch 
with all sections of the working people 
he urged them to support his reforms which he said were aimed 
at creating a society of democratic institutions and mechanisms 
that preserve and maintain law and order but we are still far from 
it 
it was not clear whether the miners new union would be allowed 
or would want to join the newly reformed national trade union 
organization whose leaders acknowledged they were losing the 
support of workers 
deputy chief vladimir scherbakov said the revamped organization 
would no longer demand a monopoly on workers loyalty 
the bidding for workers hearts in a country that once called 
itself a workers paradise shows the political importance that 
organizers place on bluecollar labor as the political and economic 
system opens up 
the miners strikes of 1989 began in protest of working and 
living conditions and shortages of such basics as soap and medical 
care 
demands quickly escalated to include regional economic autonomy 
for the main mining regions the kuznetsk basin the don river 
basin in the ukraine vorkuta in the far north and karaganda in 
kazakhstan 
prime minister nikolai i ryzhkov persuaded the miners to return 
to work promising to meet most of their demands but most of those 
promises remain unfulfilled 
the strike committees meeting at their first conference in 
donetsk last summer called for ryzhkovs government to resign 
