<TEXT>
the second of four secret policemen 
convicted of the 1984 slaying of the rev jerzy popieluszko a 
prosolidarity priest has been released from prison the 
prosecutor general said wednesday 
lt leszek pekala originally was sentenced to 15 years in prison 
after a threemonth trial that ended in february 1985 but his term 
was reduced in 1987 to six years and he was freed tuesday under a 
law that allows releases after a prisoner has served twothirds of 
his sentence 
the release was confirmed at a news conference by prosecutor 
general aleksander herzog 
popieluszko a charismatic 37yearold warsaw priest whose 
sermons bolstered the solidarity labor movement when it was 
outlawed was abducted oct 19 1984 his beaten and bound body was 
pulled from an icy river 11 days later shocking the nation and 
galvanizing the anticommunist opposition 
pekala and wlademar chmielewski were found guilty of committing 
the murder with ringleader grzegorz piotrowski their superior 
adam pietruszka also was convicted 
the public was never satisfied with the determination that no 
higherups were involved in the murder or its coverup on oct 6 
the postcommunist interior ministry reopened the case by arresting 
two former police generals on charges of masterminding the slaying 
the four convicted officers all had their sentences reduced by 
the former communist authorities and chmielewski has already been 
paroled piotrowski now is serving a 15year term due to end in 
october 1999 and pietruszkas 10year sentence is to end in 
november 1994 herzog said 
the prosecutor said the government is reviewing the supreme 
court decisions reducing the sentences and some irregularities 
are being analyzed however an extraordinary reopening of the case 
would be required to reverse the sentence reductions and the 
problem is very difficult herzog said 
