<TEXT>
amnesty international on wednesday urged president 
bush not to sign proposed legislation broadening use of the death 
penalty 
in a letter to the president the international human rights 
group said that if the proposal becomes law social justice may 
be simply ignored in the desire to seek vengeance 
the letter said amnesty was aware of at least 23 innocent 
people executed in the united states this century 
amnesty international is opposed to the death penalty in all 
cases based on our conviction that no authority has the right to 
deny anyone their most basic and fundamental human right the 
right to life itself the letter said 
david bull british section director of amnesty delivered the 
letter to the us embassy in london on wednesday 
the congressional proposals would extend the death penalty to 
some nonhomicidal offenses under federal law 
amnesty said such a move represents a dangerous departure from 
the us supreme court ruling in 1972 which stated that the death 
penalty would be cruel and unusual when applied to offenses which 
did not result in death 
a total of 138 people have been executed in the united states 
since the court in 1976 allowed states to resume use of the death 
penalty fifteen states have done so 
in its plea to bush amnesty referred to the selfevident 
racial bias in death penalty sentencing and the carrying out of 
such sentences 
the bush administration strongly supports the death penalty but 
it has threatened a veto over attempts by some congressmen to allow 
defendants to fight the death sentence by showing racial bias 
many opponents of the death penalty argue it is unfair because 
it is more often applied to blacks than whites 
amnesty also said studies have shown the death penalty is not an 
effective deterrent to violent crime or murder 
it further argued that execution methods are cruel and 
barbaric 
