<TEXT>
the senate on wednesday approved a bill 
designed to let consumers know whats in the food they eat 
the legislation would require food manufacturers to list on 
labels the amount of nutrients calories fat and salt for most 
packaged foods claims such as low salt and light would be 
clearly defined and diseaseprevention claims would have to be 
governmentapproved 
the bill passed by unanimous consent will go back to the 
house which passed a similar version in late july and was expected 
to accept the senates changes 
labeling will guarantee that advertising claims are supported 
by the facts and that consumers have the information they need to 
make wiser choices about their health and diet said sen edward 
kennedy dmass and chairman of the senate labor and human 
resources committee 
the bush administration has proposed foodlabeling regulations 
similar to the provisions of the legislation because the 
administration says the matter can be handled with regulations it 
has said in a policy statement that it opposes the bill however 
the administration has not threatened a veto 
the food and drug administration had hoped to issue final 
foodlabeling regulations by next spring requiring industry 
compliance a year later but because of differences between the 
legislation and the regulations have forced the fda to rework parts 
of its plan 
it will delay what we had been doing but we wont have to go 
back to square one said edward scarbrough acting director of 
the fdas office of nutrition and food science 
one difference between the proposed regulations and the 
legislation is that congress would require much of the nutrient 
labeling to be uniform nationwide the fda had requested comment on 
whether states should be allowed to supersede the federal 
regulations with stronger rules 
the center for science in the public interest gave the senate 
plan a qualified hurrah bruce silverglade legal director of 
the group said the days of misleading nutrition and health 
claims for most foods are coming to an end but he said he was 
concerned that cities and states would be unable to impose their 
own labeling requirements 
the national food processors association however was pleased 
with the uniformity requirement we did not get all we wanted in 
terms of federal preemption but we have a strong federal nutrition 
labeling law that will help maintain our national food distribution 
system and permit nationwide food label education programs he 
said 
under the senate measure the secretary of health and human 
services would set guidelines defining such labels as low salt 
and light food makers would have to adhere to the guidelines 
to use those terms 
also companies would need fda approval to make 
diseaseprevention claims 
restaurants would be exempt from the labeling requirements and 
foods such as fresh produce and seafood could provide nutrition 
labeling with a sign or brochure at the site of sale 
</TEXT>
