<TEXT>
the soviet parliament sought to arrest the 
collapse of central authority by passing legislation wednesday 
saying its laws supercede those of conflicting measures in the 15 
soviet republics 
three republics immediately challenged the parliamentary move 
the sponsors of the national bill said it is designed to end the 
war of laws between the national and republic governments but 
there seemed to be little way to enforce it and no promise it would 
end the jurisdictional disputes 
in defending the measure soviet lawmaker yuri kalmykov was 
quoted as saying we are neither declaring war on the republics 
nor bringing pressure to bear on them 
the republics should understand that this legal act is in the 
interests of all he said according to the state news agency 
tass kalmykov is chairman of the parliamentary committee on 
legislation in the national supreme soviet the parliament 
despite his comments the two largest soviet republics russia 
and the ukraine on wednesday passed their own laws overruling 
national legislation tass said in separate dispatches 
in addition the parliament of the baltic republic of latvia 
which declared independence this year passed a law saying 
stateowned property belongs to the republic and not to the 
national government tass said 
the latvian law overturned an oct 19 decree by soviet prime 
minister nikolai i ryzhkov he ordered that 51 percent of 
stateowned industries and businesses be sold to workers on a 
jointstock basis and the remaining 49 percent stay in the hands of 
the national government 
in its action wednesday the russian republic legislature 
meeting in moscow gave preliminary approval to laws limiting the 
authority of the national government in the republic and abolishing 
the state monopoly on land ownership tass said 
the ukrainian legislature meeting in kiev proclaimed the 
precedence of the republics laws over national laws on ukrainian 
territory national laws will enter into force in the ukraine only 
after they are ratified by the republics parliament it said 
the fragmentation of soviet power was also deepening in the 
republic of moldavia where an emergency session of parliament was 
called for thursday tass reported 
moldavian president mircha snegur said the session was needed 
because the social and economic situation in the republic has 
reached the boiling point due to declarations of independence by 
two tiny corners of moldavia a southwestern republic the 
socalled gagauz and dneister republics are seeking to separate 
themselves from moldavia 
nearly all the 15 soviet republics have declared independence or 
autonomy from the central government in moldavia georgia and the 
russian federation smaller regions have sought to distance 
themselves from republic authorities 
the law passed wednesday by the national legislature appeared to 
be a fruitless effort suspend the constitutional crisis until 
completion of a new treaty of union that soviet president mikhail 
s gorbachev is seeking to persuade the republics to negotiate 
gorbachev has had little success starting formal talks to 
replace the treaty of union which forms the legal basis of the 
national federation 
russian president boris n yeltsin and other radical reformers 
want to negotiate bilateral treaties on political and economic 
cooperation before agreeing to a new treaty of union to form a 
federation or confederation 
national legislators heatedly debated wednesdays law their 
dispute centered on a clause giving gorbachev the right to fire 
local officials who disregard national law tass said 
one house of the national legislature the council of 
nationalities approved the law without the clause the other 
house the council of the union approved it with the clause 
they later agreed on a compromise that apparently left the issue 
undecided 
