<TEXT>
jews and roman catholics met to pay homage 
to a nearly disappeared culture wednesday capping the event by 
attending a stirring concert in a synagogue scarred by neglect and 
nazi defacement 
being here and listening to the music of our people is a way 
to tell the world that we go on living said irene weingarten a 
certified public accountant from houston one of about 250 american 
jews who flew to krakow a southern polish city rich in jewish 
history to attend the event 
gilbert levine maestro of the krakow philharmonic orchestra 
conducted the concert inside the temple postepowa a 100yearold 
synagogue virtually unused since world war ii 
polands jewish community which once numbered 35 million was 
nearly wiped out by the holocaust despite the fact that fewer than 
10000 jews remain antisemitism has resurfaced in recent months 
pope john paul ii archbishop of krakow before being named 
pontiff in 1978 heartily endorsed the concert as a vehicle for 
reconciliation between the faiths said levine who was received by 
the pope at the vatican 
the chief of krakows tiny jewish congregation czeslaw 
jakobowicz said he found the concert sad but very nice 
you know we all lived together catholics and jews in this 
society for hundreds of years jakobowicz said there is no 
reason it cant be like it used to be 
levine said several highranking church officials had been 
invited to the conciliatory event for two faiths including krakow 
archbishop franciszek marcharski but local priests were the 
highest church representatives in attendance 
a letter from macharski read before the concert quoted john 
pauls words we are all children of the same god it closed 
with shalom the hebrew word for peace 
the program opened with the national anthems of poland the 
united states and israel followed by the kol nidre a traditional 
lament of jews sung during the yom kippur holiday 
the program also included works of beethoven bruch and dvorak 
the dark apricot walls and gold filigree arches and columns of 
temple postempowa reflected five decades of neglect but the 
concerts audience of 400 people sharing the small space with the 
orchestra was moved by the music many wiped away tears 
before the concert members of both faiths joined to raise a 
star of david atop the synagogue replacing one torn down by the 
gestapo in november 1939 
this will be a concert of rememberance because you cant 
forget what happened in poland 50 years ago and of hope for 
reconciliation said levine who has headed the philharmonic 
since 1987 the first american to direct an orchestra in eastern 
europe 
only a handful of jews live in krakow today their average age 
is 70 the synagogue stands in a neighborhood that has had a jewish 
presence since the 1300s 
in recent years catholicjewish relations in poland have been 
strained by the presence of carmelite nuns at the auschwitz 
concentration camp 36 miles from krakow 
over jewish protests the nuns built a convent adjoining the 
camp where 15 million jews were murdered by the nazis the church 
first promised to remove the convent in 1987 and renewed the 
promise last year but so far it has not done so 
this year also has witnessed antisemitic acts in newly 
democratized poland as well as elsewhere in eastern europe nazi 
slogans and antijewish slurs have appeared on bus stops and even 
the memorial at umschlagplatz the site in warsaw where hundreds of 
thousands of jews were sent to concentration camps 
levine whose grandfather emigrated from warsaw in 1895 and 
whose wifes mother survived auschwitz said the concert presented 
an opportunity to overcome some of the bitterness that has 
overshadowed recent dialogue between catholics and jews in poland 
music can serve a tremendously important purpose to wordlessly 
express emotions levine said but you have to have hope and a 
desire for reconciliation and for dialogue that at least goes some 
of the way toward achieving it 
</TEXT>
