<TEXT>
global warming will create food shortages that 
could eventually drive up prices by as much as 20 percent a 
leading climate expert said wednesday 
climatologist martin parry a member of the unsponsored 
intergovernmental panel on climate change forecast that higher 
temperatures and drier conditions will reduce food production 
globally by an average of 5 to 10 percent 
his report climate change and world agriculture was put 
out by earthscan a publisher of books on third world issues 
poverty and the environment 
the nearly 1 billion people who already suffer from 
malnutrition and famines would face an even greater threat to 
their survival from the combined effects of decreased agricultural 
production and the effects of higher prices for imported 
food parry told reporters at a news conference at the royal 
geographic society 
parry said farming production could fall as much as 30 percent 
in the midlatitude breadbasket regions of the world such as the 
midwestern united states canadian prairies northern european 
lowlands soviet ukraine and argentine pampas 
the regions most at risk however are those least able to cope 
such as north and west africa central america southeast asia and 
eastern brazil parry said 
his report was released five days before delegates from 100 
nations meet in geneva at the second world climate conference to 
discuss what to do about reducing carbon dioxide and other 
greenhouse gases 
such gases increase the atmospheres ability to trap heat like 
a greenhouse 
hundreds of the worlds top scientists working on the 
unsponsored climate panel have concluded that if the world 
continues emitting the gases at the current rate global avrrage 
temperatures could rise a couple degrees over the next four 
decades 
but the actual temperature increase might be even higher in some 
regions with the largest rises in higher latitudes said parry a 
professor at birmingham university 
in the wheat and maize regions of europe and north america 
production could be cut by 20 percent with a 2 degree centigrade 
rise in temperature 
the result could be increased costs of food for consumers in 
those regions smaller cereal crops for export and higher prices 
in the world cereal market 
