<TEXT>
congress on wednesday approved and sent to 
president bush legislation aimed at improving the security of air 
travelers against terrorism 
the bill which grew out of recommendations of a commission that 
studied the 1988 pan am flight 103 bombing authorizes up to 7 
million for security improvements in the fiscal year which began 
oct 1 
transportation secretary samuel skinner welcomed the action and 
said he would recommend that president bush sign it 
skinner in a statement called the measure a signficant 
milestone for the families of the victims of the pan am 103 
tragedy and everyone who flies 
paul hudson chairman of the families group families of pan 
am 103lockerbie said in a statement families of the victims 
feel elated and relieved 
the bill would require the government to issue guidelines for 
warning passengers of potential terrorist threats would create a 
new post at the transportation department to press for security 
improvements and would require intelligence agencies to share 
terrorism information with the department 
rather than face a veto the house and senate amended the bill 
to give the administration flexibility to decide whether to force 
airlines to buy and use expensive explosive detection devices 
widely criticized for unreliability 
the federal aviation administration wanted to make airlines 
acquire 150 of the thermal neutron analysis devices at a total 
cost of 175 million and deploy them at 15 international airports 
in the united states and 25 abroad 
but a test of the device by a presidential commission that 
investigated the pan am bombing over lockerbie scotland showed 
that it could not detect an amount of plastic explosive like that 
used in the bombing and also avoid false alarms 
the final bill allows the faa to order limited use of the 
devices but only for 18 months until better technology is 
developed 
many of the reforms called for in the bill already have been put 
in place by the government and skinner said the measure would 
ensure that the changes are lasting 
</TEXT>
