<TEXT>
ornithologists were elated this week 
by the sighting of an elusive night parrot a species that hasnt 
been seen officially in nearly 80 years 
thats the good news 
the bad is that the emerald green and yellowspotted bird was 
found dead at the side of a roadway in queensland state the likely 
victim of a cars windshield 
i was just standing there and i looked down at my feet and 
there it was said walter boles an ornithologist at the 
australian museum in an interview thursday in the sydney morning 
herald 
the night parrot was considered by some experts to be extinct 
with the last official sighting in 1912 in western australia state 
the bird first was collected on the edge of the simpson desert in 
south australia state by explorer john stuart in 1845 
the species is strictly nocturnal and lives on the ground in the 
desert flying only when disturbed boles said 
he was returning from a twomonth museum expedition to western 
australia when his group stopped to look at some other birds on the 
road south of mount isa about 940 miles northwest of brisbane 
boles said he was standing near his vehicle by the roadside 
waiting for a second vehicle to catch up when he spotted the 
birds corpse at his feet 
i knew what it was straight away said boles i picked it 
up and casually showed it to wayne longmore an associate he just 
yelled over and over for the next 10 minutes 
the discovery may cost australian geographic publisher dick 
smith 39000 last year he offered that reward 50000 australian 
dollars for conclusive evidence the night parrot still existed 
one condition of the reward was that the bird not be killed 
purposely a magazine official said thursday that since the 
vehicle that hit the parrot probably did not do so purposely the 
reward would likely be paid once the dead birds identity is 
verified 
