budget negotiators all but reached final 
agreement wednesday on a longsought plan to slash the federal 
deficit by boosting taxes on the wealthy raising levies on 
gasoline and increasing costs for medicare recipients 
the white house said final details remained to be worked out 
but sufficient progress has been made to allow bush to sign 
another emergency bill to keep the government operating through 
saturday when lawmakers hope to finish their budget business for 
the year 
the house approved the measure 38045 the fourth temporary 
extension of federal spending this month and the senate passed it 
by voice vote 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said all federal workers 
should report to work as scheduled thursday bush will not actually 
sign the stopgap bill until thursday morning 
earlier house speaker thomas s foley dwash said a budget 
compromise might be wrapped up in time to reach the floor for a 
vote thursday he said democrats had reached a very very strong 
consensus to support the package an important development 
because most house republicans were ready to oppose the plan but 
