they joined because it paid well offered 
them a fine education and a nice home put them in a position of 
power and privilege 
to many working for the east german secret police was a 
glamorous and exciting way to make a living 
no longer the fear and obedience the socalled stasi once 
instilled have been replaced by open hostility the professions 
prized perks have slipped away 
peter kuntze now shovels coal on the college campus where he was 
once a highly paid professor of criminology an elite member of an 
exclusive club 
for 16 years he worked as a stasi detective who dissected 
information on his countrymen for nearly two decades after that 
he trained new generations of stasi officers 
now kuntze is a 54yearold laborer working in the boiler room 
that supplies heat to the old stasi spy school now a teachers 
college specializing in language and music 
i dont regret my work for the stasi said kuntze a father 
of five i only regret that i put my heart and soul into it im 
now in a position where i can only do unskilled labor 
dietrich fischer 52 once specialized in tracking down western 
spies a very analytical job he found quite exciting today 
the former stasi colonel works as headmaster of a kindergarten 
instead of foreign agents he keeps track of squealing children 
everyone thinks its comical he says smiling 
because of the stifling hold they kept on society because of 
the paranoia and dread they created the hatred for these people 
remains intense in what was east germany 
what to do with them is one of the deep social dilemmas 
confronting the united germany as it brings the old communist 
society the oppressed and the oppressors together into a free 
world 
contrary to popular belief most stasi agents are not hiding 
most are still out there mixing in the new society holding jobs 
or looking for them 
after years of serving as a governments iron fist on a cowed 
society however it is the oncefeared stasi who now fear the 
people 
one of the most cloistered pockets of this privileged elite used 
to be the old stasi officers college outside golm a small village 
about 25 miles southwest of berlin 
the school was a topsecret invitationonly training center 
that offered a broad education to only the brightest young officer 
candidates 
about 30 gray blocklike buildings stand on the end of a 
winding secluded road the campus is an incongruous icily 
intimidating mix of ivycovered walls and highsecurity fences 
the school was closed in january and turned over to the 
teachers college in nearby potsdam 
much of the old faculty still lives in a 30house neighborhood 
near campus a horseshoeshaped complex of neat homes with spacious 
yards and private car ports 
the people here say the land has been put in public trust to be 
sold their offers to buy their homes have been spurned the 
telephone system has been removed 
most of them personally deny the allegations of stasi brutality 
and corruption now chronicled daily in the german press all 
nations have secret services they say 
if someone says something against us its impossible to prove 
it wrong says kuntze people can say whatever they want 
kuntze joined the stasi in 1956 because the pay and 
opportunities were so good he said he specialized in collating 
information weighing its accuracy and value 
as a teacher he taught prospective stasi officers how to 
develop informants 
it was part of the work nothing negative he said 
unofficial sources were necessary to any secret service 
one of the stasis jobs was to check the pulse of public 
sentiment but kuntze said this information often was ignored or 
lost in labyrinthine bureaucracy 
if the information had been exploited in the right way there 
would have been changes that would have precluded last autumns 
revolution he said 
of the 85000 people who worked for the stasi about 
4500050000 were actual field agents each of whom had two or 
three paid informants in workplaces or schools he said 
former agents say potential stasi recruits were singled out 
early often as young as 13 
they were watched for years kuntze said people were excluded if 
they demonstrated an inordinate amount of fear gossiped too much 
or had relatives in the west 
ullrich heidenreich followed such a career path 
fashionably dressed and lounging in a handsomely furnished 
living room the 34yearold heidenreich and his wife martina 
could be any upwardly mobile young couple 
the son of a police officer he was recruited when he was 16 and 
joined two years later he worked as a stasi guard on the 
czechoslovak border then as an operative in karl marx city 
like other top recruits he was sent to school he was trained 
as a lawyer and became a professor at the stasi school 
unlike other teachers he found a job in his field after he was 
fired 
heidenreich now teaches law at a police academy in potsdam he 
teaches west german law which he spent nine months studying 
he does not expect to keep this job once a united german 
government takes a closer look at the people on its public 
payrolls 
but hes optimistic about finding new work 
people who are competent hold positions of responsibility 
he said people who are incompetent want us out those who have 
nothing try to drive the bright ones out by shouting stasi 
the couple are prepared to move west to advance their careers 
this virulent campaign against the stasi is really a symptom 
of the east he said in the west people are more realistic 
here there is too much emotion 
the former stasi captain has no qualms about shifting his 
ideology nor apologies about his past 
as long as you are socially well off you dont ask questions 
and you dont rock the boat he said 
im not saying i was convinced that what i did was wrong when 
i worked for the stasi i believed it was right he said im 
only saying that i can learn the new way 
communist party and stasi officials were well paid with 
tremendous perks and fine homes heidenreich said he and his wife 
have a lot of money but not as a much as people think 
kuntze fischer and heidenreich all made about 3000 marks 
about 1950 a month as teachers more than triple the average 
east german wage 
kuntze and fischer say they make about onethird that now 
heidenreich makes about 1900 marks 1250 
some have not done so well 
juergen kanis 34 has a law degree in a legal system that no 
longer exists a marxistleninist philosophy doctorate in a 
capitalist nation and no job in a free market 
kanis a father of two says he has lost three jobs in the last 
year because of his stasi past 
the stasi recruited him as farm boy and sent him to karl marx 
university it gave him a job and turned him into a teacher of the 
ideology that created it 
that was the way things were in those days kanis said 
if the cia came to you would you say no he asks 
</TEXT>
