<TEXT>
few sectors of east german society scaped the 
scrutiny of the stasi the communist secret police created an aura 
of paranoia that still lingers 
more than 85000 people were members more than twice that 
number were informers who worked in factories businesses and 
schools 
east german workers and students were broken down into small 
manageable work groups former agents say each such group contained 
at least one paid informant 
about 9000 stasi members monitored telephone conversations 
people considered to be nonconformists were denied good jobs and 
housing their mail was disrupted many were jailed on trumpedup 
charges others beaten 
border guards all stasi members killed people who tried to 
flee the country 
stasi agents regularly interviewed government officials and 
factory bosses the conversations were taped transcribed and 
filed 
many former stasi officials and communist party functionaries 
are believed to have a disproportionate share of the wealth 
property and businesses in what was east germany 
david gill of the committee overseeing the stasis dissolution 
said most members are working in factories on pensions or 
unemployed but many run established businesses or have parlayed 
connections and money into new ones 
lawmakers are debating whether to grant amnesty to some stasi 
members and prosecute others 
the stasi foreign unit acted as an espionage agency about 60 
stasi spies have been arrested in recent months in what formerly 
was west germany 
erich mielke former chief of the stasi is in jail awaiting 
prosecution on charges of corruption harboring leftist terrorists 
and other crimes 
