democrats expect to improve their hold on the 
nations governorships this year but they face tough battles to 
wrest control of the largest states from the republicans 
ohio gov richard celeste the head of the democratic governors 
association predicts a net gain of one to four governorships for 
his party this year 
republicans who gained eight seats when many of these same 
governors were up four years ago would be content just to hold 
their own this time 
democrats have the upper hand in the nations statehouses going 
into the elections controlling 29 governorships to the gops 21 
but the party that controls the biggest states will be pleased no 
matter the outcome of the rest 
much more important than the raw number of gains or losses is 
which states go which way says political analyst charlie cook 
unlike house or senate seats all governorships are not created 
equal and it is the megastates this year that really count 
the reason is redistricting legislatures will draw new 
congressional district lines next year that may change of face of 
their us house delegations both parties would like to hold the 
veto stamp in states facing big gains or losses in their 
congressional delegations 
republicans control the governorships in four of the biggest 
states that are up this year california texas florida and 
illinois 
californias legislature will figure out how to distribute as 
many as seven new congressional seats next year based on the 
states population gain in preliminary census figures democrats 
control the legislature there and republicans say they need the 
governorship to ensure a fair map 
texas and florida will gain new house seats too while illinois 
stands to lose two seats 
