<TEXT>
when the stock market decline becomes too much 
to take it may be time to look into the future to dream a bit of 
wonderfully bullish times when you can awaken each day to prospects 
of profits 
it has been many months since people enjoyed such days and it 
might be a long time before they experience them again the 
economic base that stock prices reflect has serious and maybe 
worsening problems 
still history declares that somewhere out in the future are 
better times how far out depends on your sense of time if you 
view a few months as a long time you might be disappointed if you 
think in terms of years you wont be 
did you know that even in the decade of the 1930s when stocks 
floundered after the great crash of 1929 the annual loss from 
equities was 01 percent barely into the minus column 
purists will point out of course that much of the collapse 
occurred in the final year before the decade of the 1930s but 
historians counter by pointing to another downturn in 1931 and 
still another in 1938 
in no decade since then has the average annual return been a 
minus that is the total return for the decade broken down to an 
annual basis in each of those decades however prices bounced 
like a golf ball on a highway 
in all there have been 11 bear markets since the 1930s 
including the present one and another that spanned the turn of the 
decade from 1939 to the spring of 1942 
in each one prices fell sharply 48 percent in 19731974 but 
only one lasted more than three years that was the 37month bear 
market from may 1946 to june 1949 in each instance of course 
prices resumed their rise 
wright investors service arrived at the 01 percent loss for 
the 1930s by using this calculation 
it started with an earned return of minus 02 percent a year 
from 55 percent annual dividend income and a 57 percent decline 
of earnings to that was added an increase of 01 percent a year in 
priceearnings ratios 
using the same formula the return for the 1940s averaged 92 
percent a year rose to 194 percent in the 1950s fell back to 78 
percent in the 1960s and to 59 percent in the 1970s but then 
leaped to 175 percent in the 1980s 
you are not convinced by the historical record nothing unusual 
about that such despair is one of the identifying traits of a bear 
market as surely as unjustified optimism identifies a bull market 
heading to a disastrous finale 
equity investments require faith as well as information they 
are risky simply because nobody knows anything for certain about 
the future very little about the present and probably only 
slightly more than that about the past 
that said here are wrights projections for the period through 
1995 
dividend income will grow an average of 34 percent a year and 
earnings 81 percent giving an earned return of 115 percent pe 
ratios however will be lowered by 26 percent a year leaving an 
annual return of 89 percent 
based partly on those estimates wright projects the dow jones 
industrials to average 2750 points in 1991 rising to 2975 in 
1991 to 3175 in 1993 to 3413 in 1994 and to 3625 points in 
1995 
nothing like the period 19851990 when the average almost 
doubled from 1547 points but a relatively serene sea nonetheless 
for those investors who in 1990 saw their stocks engulfed in the 
maelstrom 
