maytag corp on wednesday named a new 
managing director to its hoover appliance business in britain as 
part of what it called a major reorganization of the european 
business 
hoovers appliance and floor care operation in the united 
kingdom has been a drain on maytag profitability since maytag 
acquired the business in a 1989 takeover of the chicago pacific 
corp 
daniel krumm maytags chairman announced the latest in a 
series of steps to shore up the british operations in remarks to 
employees at hoover production facilities in england scotland and 
wales he said the plan is designed to achieve the rebirth 
rejuvenation stability and return to profitability of hoover uk 
krumm named veteran labor relations executive william foust to 
succeed anthony williamson as managing director of hoover uk and to 
head a task force to speed organizational changes and implement 
production efficiencies 
foust is the senior vice president of human resources at maytag 
and a former officer of the magic chef co another maytag 
subsidiary krumm said foust will serve full time in south wales 
until he completes the special assignment then return to maytags 
headquarters in the central iowa community of newton 
williamson who has worked for hoover for more than 30 years 
announced he intends to retire but will continue to serve as a 
director and to represent hoover with various industry 
associations 
the shakeup was no surprise said analyst russell leavitt who 
follows maytag for the new york investment firm salomon brothers 
that business has suffered in the last year or two 
essentially since they got it leavitt said he said maytag 
executives were dissatisfied with the performance of hoover uk but 
probably needed time to understand industry conditions in britain 
which has been hit by a major slump in its appliance business 
maytag which does not disclose results from hoover uk last 
week reported a 157 million operating loss from european 
operations for the first nine months of the year compared with an 
operating loss of 83 million a year earlier the hoover uk 
operations were a big contributor to the operating loss said 
maytag spokeswoman lisa mendheim 
