standard amp poors corp one of the nations two 
major creditrating agencies on wednesday downgraded its rating of 
5 billion worth of debt of chemical banking corp and several 
subsidiaries 
the downgrade of the nations sixthlargest banking company 
followed a similar rating reduction last month by sampp affecting no 
2 chase manhattan corp 
sampp said its downgrade of new yorkbased chemical reflected its 
expectation of further moderate deterioration in loan quality in 
a continued difficult operating environment 
however the rating agency tempered its concern with optimistic 
statements about chemicals prospects 
the company has the liquidity and financial flexibility to deal 
with the expected loan problems it said it added that 
chemicals recent decision to reduce its dividend payment should 
help it rebuild capital after the heavy losses of the past few 
years 
chemical spokesman charles salmans said the company was 
disappointed by the action sampp in its own announcement notes the 
quality of chemicals loan portfolio and the steps we have taken to 
build capital he said 
sampp lowered by one notch the senior debt rating of parent 
chemical banking and subsidiaries texas commerce bancshares and 
chemical new york 
it also lowered by one degree its rating on certifas soon as possible 
us bankruptcy judge harold c abramson wednesday set a dec 14 
hearing on the confirmation plan and company spokeswoman cecilia 
stubbs norwood said southland hoped to emerge from court 
supervision before the end of the year 
ms norwood said store operations would not be affected by the 
filing and the company had commitments for 400 million in 
financing while it proceeds through the bankruptcy process 
southland has been struggling since 1987 when the founding 
thompson family fearing a takeover by the belzbergs of canada 
took the company private in a 49 billion leveraged buyout 
the lbo second highest ever at the time became more expensive 
on oct 19 1987 when the dow jones industrial average plunged 508 
points the crash made it more difficult and more expensive to 
arrange financing for the deal 
southland first proposed its restructuring in march of this 
year acknowledging that dwindling profits would make it impossible 
to meet the debt brought on by the 1987 buyout 
in april southland revealed a fourthquarter loss of 101 
billion as it wrote off goodwill from the buyout the company 
denied the writeoff proved the thompsons paid too much in the 
buyout but only reflected a decline in the value of the company 
assets 
at first southland proposed selling 75 percent of the company 
for 400 million to itoyokado co ltd and seveneleven japan co 
ltd its japanese franchisees 
the thompson family would keep 15 percent and the creditors 
would get the rest along with new securities 
but enough bondholders would not go along in july the japanese 
agreed to take a smaller piece of the company 70 percent and 
provide more money 430 million the thompsons also agreed to cut 
their holdings to 5 percent while creditors got 25 percent of the 
reorganized company in addition to improved terms on their bonds 
however creditors forced southland to require that 95 percent 
of the bondholders go along before they would agree to the swap 
and the threshold proved too high to meet by this weeks deadline 
although the reorganization plan mirrors the restructuring 
proposal it now must be approved by a bankruptcy court and could 
still face objections 
if it succeeds it will end the thompson familys control of the 
company none of the three brothers who run southland would comment 
on the bankruptcy ms norwood said 
