<TEXT>
when halloween decorations come down this week 
and stores start putting up christmas trees and wreaths retailers 
will begin what is expected to be their bleakest holiday season in 
years 
the faltering economy and the persian gulf crisis already have 
put a big crimp in consumer spending with retail sales falling 
dramatically in august and september no one realistically expects 
shoppers to put caution aside when they start looking for gifts 
its going to be a tough christmas said jeffrey edelman a 
retail industry analyst with barclays de zoete wedd inc the only 
question is how bad is it going to be 
daniel barry of kidder peabody amp co was more blunt i think 
this is going to be one of the worst christmases in two decades 
retailers also are expecting a difficult season 
kenneth macke chairman of dayton hudson corp said his 
company like most retailers is planning conservatively to meet 
the uncertain mood of american consumers 
theyve got job insecurity and oil prices are up macke said 
of consumers if they had a definite answer to some of these 
things wed be better off 
christmas has been something of a guessing game in recent years 
with consumers shopping later in the season and the outcome not 
certain until after all the receipts are tallied 
many observers believe there wont be any suspense this year 
especially since late summer sales considered a harbinger of the 
christmas season were so poor for instance mackes stores 
which include dayton hudson marshall field target and mervyns 
suffered a 2 percent drop in sales in september 
we have a consumer thats really pulling back said walter 
loeb a retailing consultant and analyst he doesnt like 2 a 
gallon gas he doesnt like higher taxes he doesnt like 
unemployment 
there are more americans out of work now than there were a year 
ago the unemployment rate was on an upswing in september rising 
to 57 percent while last december it was holding steady at 53 
percent a consumer who is not working is not going to spend a lot 
on christmas gifts 
even those with secure jobs are scaling back giftgiving plans 
since oil prices shot higher following the aug 2 iraqi invasion of 
kuwait americans have been shelling out more money for gasoline 
and heating oil and have less for extras like gifts 
about the only thing that would keep christmas from being a 
disaster is an end to the mideast crisis and a drop in oil 
prices said barry the kidder peabody analyst 
