merchandise could be more vulnerable to sluggish sales our 
experience is that the consumer has tended to trade down he 
said 
that means there likely will be more ties books and sweaters 
bought this season than stereo sets and expensive jewelry 
apparel retailers may also find themselves in a bind they were 
among the hardest hit as sales dropped in late summer 
for example j c penney whose business grew modestly in the 
late spring and early summer saw its sales fall 24 percent and 
34 percent respectively in august and september specialty apparel 
retailer limited inc which posted moderate increases in the 
spring managed only a 1 percent gain in august and suffered a 3 
percent decline in september 
one segment of the industry likely to fare somewhat better this 
christmas is toy retailers parents may scrimp on gifts for adults 
so their children find plenty of presents under the tree on dec 
25 
santa claus gets first priority on the dollar said macke 
inventory will be a key to how successful this christmas will 
be macke said his stores have bought conservatively and focused on 
the kinds of merchandise that are expected to be the biggest 
movers 
but a wild card that can make or break the season is how much 
retailers are forced to take price markdowns 
markdowns have become almost commonplace in the last few years 
and most analysts expect there will be pricecutting again this 
christmas 
edelman the barclays de zoete wedd analyst predicted markdowns 
would not be quite as severe as in christmas 1989 
last year units of allied stores corp and federated department 
stores inc reduced prices sharply to bring in cash in a futile 
attempt at avoiding bankruptcy court other retailers were forced 
to follow suit to compete and bottom lines that quarter the most 
crucial earings period for retailers were the casualties 
barry took a more pessimistic view of markdowns in the upcoming 
season and had this advice for consumers do your christmas 
shopping late therell be plenty of merchandise at bargain 
prices 
if dayton hudsons sales appear to be falling short of 
projections macke said his stores will try to avoid heavy 
markdowns by reducing expenses 
yet in spite of the sofar glum outlook for the season some say 
it is still possible retailers will be pleasantly surprised 
karen sack an analyst with standard amp poors corp said that 
while consumers have definitely cut back spending i suspect they 
will spend for christmas 
macke despite his conservative outlook said i wouldnt be a the 
threatened 
northern spotted owl and also rejected a move to cut the forest 
service roadbuilding effort in half 
